gmx:name.gco:CharacterString: Feature catalog for Licensed Healthcare Facilities, California, 2006

gmx:scope.gco:CharacterString: Clinics; Hospitals; Health facilities; Community health services

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: Unique key identifying a licensed healthcare facility that reports data to the California Office of Statewide Health Planning and Development.
Healthcare facility license number issued by the California Department of Health Services [CDHS].
Internal system key tracking license information in ALIRTS.
Internal system key tracking address information in ALIRTS.
Internal system key tracking facility information in ALIRTS.
Internal system key tracking legal entity information in ALIRTS.
Unique key identifying a healthcare facility; equivalent to Facility Number used by OSHPD Facilities Development Division [FDD].
Healthcare facility name as presented on state license.
Healthcare facility name; string length shortened for cartographic usability.
Facility street address listed on license; number and name.
Secondary facility address listed on license; Suite, PO box, etc.
Date of latest update to address from the OSHPD ALIRTS system.
City name listed on the facility license issued by California Dept of Public Health, Licensing and Certification.
ZIP Code listed on facility license; five-digit ZIP Code only.
Healthcare facility contact name derived from utilization report stored in ALIRTS.
Healthcare facility contact phone number derived from utilization reports stored in ALIRTS.
Code identifying healthcare facility type. Code is used as first digit of OSHPD_ID
Status of the healthcare facility license as issued by the Calfornia Department of Health Services [CDHS]. Value correlates with status_id attribute.
Code identifying status of the healthcare facility license. Coded value correlates with fac_status attribute.
Facility is designated a Disproportionate Share Hospital [DSH] by the California Department of Health Services [CDHS]. (boolean)
Metropolitan Area as defined by the U.S. Office of Management and Budget [OMB]. (boolean)
Describes the type of healthcare facility as licensed by the California Department of Health Services [CDHS].
Code identifying the type of healthcare facility as licensed by California Department of Health Services [CDHS].
Describes the category of healthcare facility as licensed by the California Department of Health Services [CDHS]. Values correlate with 'categry_id' attribute.
Date for the latest status condition according to the latest license recieved by OSHPD in the ALIRTS system.
Urbanized Area as defined by the U.S. Census Bureau (boolean)
Code identifying the category of healthcare facility as licensed by the California Department of Health Services [CDHS]. Values correlate with 'category' attribute.
Describes the category of control (ownership) of the healthcare facility licensee.
Describes the category and type of control (ownership) of the healthcare facility licensee.
Rural area as defined by the Rural-Urban Commuting Area [RUCA] classification system, as applied by the federal Office of Rural Health Policy [ORHP]. (boolean)
Facility is designated a Rural Hospital as listed in the California Health and Safety Code, Section 1250. (boolean)
Facility is designated a Critical Access Hospital [CAH] by the California Department of Health Services [CDHS]. (boolean)
State abbreviation listed on facility license.
Facility is designated a Federally Qualified Health Center [FQHC] by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services [CMS]. (boolean)
Last 4 digits of 9 digit ZIP Code
Facility is designated a Federally Qualified Health Center [FQHC] Look-Alike by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services [CMS]. (boolean)

Address geocoding match score on scale of 0-100. Higher scores are generally better, but it will depend on which data was used to perform the geocode. Geocoding is the process of converting an address string into a map coordinate such as Latitude/Longitude.

Health Service Area [HSA] is a geographic area consisting of one or more contiguous counties, previously designated by the federal Department of Health and Human Services for health planning on a regional basis.
Service Planning Area [SPA] ia a geographic area designated by Los Angeles County, within the County, for healthcare planning purposes.
California Office of Emergency Services [OES] administrative region.
OSHPD Facilities Development Division [FDD] administrative region.
Identifies a Medical Service Study Area [MSSA].
Medical Service Study Areas are defined as either Urban, Rural, or Frontier based on established population criteria.
Total number of licensed beds housed by the healthcare facility as reported by the Department of Health Services [CDHS].
Trauma Center Designation level of the hospital as reported by the California Emergency Medical Services Authority [EMSA].
Level I and II trauma centers have similar personnel, services, and resource requirements with the greatest difference being that Level Is are research and teaching facilities.
Level I and II trauma centers have similar personnel, services, and resource requirements with the greatest difference being that Level Is are research and teaching facilities.

gfc:label.gco:CharacterString: Level I Trauma and Level II Pediatric Trauma Center

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: Level I and II Pediatric Trauma Centers focus specifically on pediatric trauma patients. Level Is require some additional pediatric specialties and are research and teaching facilities.

gfc:label.gco:CharacterString: Level II Trauma and Level II Pediatric Trauma Center

gfc:definition.gco:CharacterString: Level I and II Pediatric Trauma Centers focus specifically on pediatric trauma patients. Level Is require some additional pediatric specialties and are research and teaching facilities.
Level III and IV trauma centers generally provide initial stabilization of trauma patients with the greatest difference being surgical capabilities at the Level III facilities.
Level III and IV trauma centers generally provide initial stabilization of trauma patients with the greatest difference being surgical capabilities at the Level III facilities.
